sorders","Advanced maternal age","Cervical factors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most common female factor requiring IVF is \u003Cstrong\u003Etubal disease\u003C/strong\u003E, which prevents the natural meeting of sperm and egg in the fallopian tubes. This can result from previous pelvic inflammatory disease, surgery, or endometriosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other factors are less common causes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometriosis\u003C/strong\u003E affects fertility through multiple mechanisms but is less common than tubal disease as a primary indication for IVF\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvulatory disorders\u003C/strong\u003E can often be treated with other fertility treatments before IVF is required\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E may affect implantation but are rarely the sole indication for IVF\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical factors\u003C/strong\u003E are an uncommon primary indication for IVF\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the predominance of tubal disease helps explain why IVF, which bypasses the need for functioning fallopian tubes, is such an effective treatment option.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tubal disease is the most common female factor requiring in vitro fertilisation","Fallopian tube damage can result from infection, surgery, or endometriosis","Tubal disease prevents natural fertilisation by blocking sperm-egg interaction"],"references":["Wang J, Sauer MV. In vitro fertilization (IVF): a review of 3 decades of clinical innovation and technological advancement. Ther Clin Risk Manag. 2006 Dec;2(4):355-64. doi: 10.2147/tcrm.2006.2.4.355. PMID: 18360648; PMCID: PMC1936357","Choe J, Shanks AL. In Vitro Fertilization. [Updated 2023 Sep 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publi